            <h1>Analysis Methods</h1>
            <section>
                <h2>1. Overview</h2>
                <p>The analysis systematically measures how closely current U.S. economic indicator trends resemble the
                    pre-recession periods of eight historical U.S. recessions. Rather than relying on visual inspection
                    alone, two quantitative metrics are computed for every combination of recession, indicator, and time
                    window — producing a composite similarity score from 0 to 100.</p>

                <br>
                <h2>2. Indicators</h2>
                <p>For comparison with current data, we are not going to use Inflation data as the last updated data was
                    in 2024.</p>
                <br>
                <h2>3. Time Windows Compared</h2>
                <p>For each recession, indicator data was extracted for six look-back windows ending at the month before
                    the recession officially began. The same windows were applied to current data ending March 2026.
                </p>

                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Window</th>
                            <th>Interpretation</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1 Month</strong></td>
                            <td>Very near-term momentum — the most recent trend direction</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Short-term trend — captures early shifts in indicator direction</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>3 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Quarter-level trend — most useful for fast-moving indicators (VIX, Oil, SP500)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>6 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Medium-term trend — captures policy-response lags (e.g. Fed rate decisions)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1 Year</strong></td>
                            <td>One-year arc — most useful for slow-moving indicators (Unemployment, Interest)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2 Years</strong></td>
                            <td>Full cycle view — captures the macro environment leading into a recession</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <br>
                <h2>4. Metric 1 — Spearman Rank Correlation</h2>
                <p>Spearman Rank Correlation measures the monotonic relationship between two sequences. Unlike Pearson
                    correlation which looks for strict linear relationships, Spearman checks whether the values go up
                    and down together, even if the scale or rate of change varies. The raw output is a coefficient
                    from -1 to +1, where:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>+1.0</strong> means perfect positive correlation — the two series move in the exact
                        same direction at the same time.</li>
                    <li><strong>0.0</strong> means no monotonic relationship — the movements are unrelated.</li>
                    <li><strong>-1.0</strong> means perfect inverse correlation — the series move in completely
                        opposite directions.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>In the context of this analysis, Spearman is used because economic indicators often move together
                    without following a perfectly linear relationship. For example, unemployment may broadly rise
                    alongside interest rates before a recession, but not at a constant proportional rate. Spearman
                    captures this kind of directional similarity more robustly than Pearson.</p>
                <p>The raw Spearman value is rescaled from [-1, +1] to [0, 100] to make it compatible with the
                    composite score, using the formula: <code>Spearman Score = (ρ + 1) / 2 × 100</code>.</p>
                <p>A high score (near 100) indicates the two time series move in the exact same direction at the same
                    time. A low score (near 0) indicates the series move in completely opposite directions, showing
                    no similarity in trend.</p>
                <details style="margin-top: 10px; text-align: left; cursor: pointer;">
                    <summary style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--link-color);">Show Code</summary>
                    <pre
                        style="background: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.85rem; text-align: left; cursor: auto; margin-top: 10px;"><code>def spearman_similarity(a: np.ndarray, b: np.ndarray) -> float:
    """
    Spearman rank correlation rescaled from [-1,1] to [0,100].
    Values near 100 mean the two series move in exactly the same direction.
    Returns 50 (neutral) when one series is constant.
    """
    if len(a) < 3 or np.std(a) == 0 or np.std(b) == 0:
        return 50.0
    r, _ = spearmanr(a, b)
    # Map [-1, 1] → [0, 100]
    return (r + 1) / 2 * 100</code></pre>
                </details>

                <br>
                <h2>5. Metric 2 — Dynamic Time Warping (DTW)</h2>
                <p>Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) measures how similar two curves look, even if one is slightly
                    shifted in time. For example, if unemployment spiked one month later in a past recession compared
                    to today, DTW can still recognise that the overall shape is the same.</p>
                <p>Before comparing, each series is scaled to a common range of [0, 1] so that indicators with very
                    different units (e.g. Oil in dollars vs Unemployment as a percentage) can be compared fairly.</p>
                <p>DTW produces a distance — a smaller distance means the two curves look more alike. We convert this
                    into a score from 0 to 100 where higher means more similar:
                    <code>DTW Score = (1 - distance / max_distance) × 100</code>.
                </p>
                <p>A high score (near 100) means the shapes of the two series closely match. A low score means the
                    shapes are very different.</p>

                <details style="margin-top: 10px; text-align: left; cursor: pointer;">
                    <summary style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--link-color);">Show Code</summary>
                    <pre
                        style="background: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.85rem; text-align: left; cursor: auto; margin-top: 10px;"><code>def dtw_similarity(a: np.ndarray, b: np.ndarray) -> float:
    """
    Dynamic Time Warping distance converted to a similarity score [0, 100].
    DTW handles slight phase shifts better than plain Euclidean distance.

    We normalise the raw DTW distance by the maximum possible distance
    (all-ones vs all-zeros for min-max scaled data) so results are comparable
    across different window lengths.
    """
    if len(a) < 2 or len(b) < 2:
        return 50.0

    # dtaidistance expects float64 arrays
    a64 = a.astype(np.float64)
    b64 = b.astype(np.float64)

    dist = dtw.distance_fast(a64, b64)

    # Maximum possible DTW distance for sequences of this length (all 0 vs all 1)
    max_dist = np.sqrt(len(a))  # rough upper bound for [0,1] normalised data

    similarity = max(0.0, (1 - dist / max_dist)) * 100
    return similarity</code></pre>
                </details>

                <br>
                <h2>6. 1-Year Trend Comparison</h2>
                <p>For each indicator, the model extracts the 12 months of data leading up to today and the 12 months leading up to each historical recession start. Both series are normalised to a [0, 1] scale so that indicators with different units can be compared fairly.</p>
                <p>Both the Spearman and DTW scores are then computed on these 12-month windows — meaning the scores reflect how similar the entire year-long trend looks, not any single month in isolation. A high score means the shape of the current 12-month trajectory closely resembles how that indicator behaved in the year before a past recession.</p>

                <h3>Example</h3>
                <p>Say we are comparing unemployment today against the 1973 recession. After extracting and normalising both series, we get two 12-month arrays:</p>
                <pre style="background: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.85rem; text-align: left; margin-bottom: 15px;"><code>Current (2025):      [0.10, 0.15, 0.20, 0.28, 0.35, 0.42, 0.50, 0.55, 0.60, 0.70, 0.75]
1973 recession:      [0.12, 0.18, 0.23, 0.30, 0.38, 0.45, 0.52, 0.57, 0.63, 0.68, 0.72, 0.78]</code></pre>
                
                <p>Both arrays are fed into the similarity functions in one go:</p>
                <pre style="background: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.85rem; text-align: left; margin-bottom: 15px;"><code>spearman_similarity([0.10, 0.15, ...], [0.12, 0.18, ...]) -> 0.98 -> rescaled to 99
dtw_similarity([0.10, 0.15, ...], [0.12, 0.18, ...])      -> 0.95 -> rescaled to 95</code></pre>

                <p>Both scores are high because the two series rise steadily at the same pace — the shapes are nearly identical. This would place the 1973 recession among the top matches for unemployment.</p>

                <details style="margin-top: 10px; text-align: left; cursor: pointer;">
                    <summary style="font-weight: bold; color: var(--link-color);">Show Code</summary>
                    <pre style="background: #f4f4f4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 5px; overflow-x: auto; font-size: 0.85rem; text-align: left; cursor: auto; margin-top: 10px;"><code>def plot_overlay_per_indicator(df: pd.DataFrame, results: pd.DataFrame, metric: str = "Spearman"):
    window_label = "1 Year"
    n_months = TIME_WINDOWS[window_label]

    top_matches = (
        results[results["Window"] == window_label]
        .sort_values(metric, ascending=False)
        .groupby("Indicator")
        .head(2)
    )

    indicators = list(INDICATORS.keys())

    for indicator in indicators:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(14, 5))
        curr = extract_window(df, CURRENT_END, n_months)[indicator].dropna()
        curr_norm = normalise(curr)
        x_curr = np.linspace(-n_months, 0, len(curr_norm))
        ax.plot(x_curr, curr_norm.values, color="black", linewidth=2.5,
                label="Current (2024–2026)", zorder=5)

        colors = ["#e41a1c", "#377eb8"]
        indicator_matches = top_matches[top_matches["Indicator"] == indicator]

        for i, (_, row) in enumerate(indicator_matches.iterrows()):
            recession_start = RECESSIONS[row["Recession"]]
            hist = extract_window(df, recession_start, n_months)[indicator].dropna()
            hist_norm = normalise(hist)
            x_hist = np.linspace(-n_months, 0, len(hist_norm))
            label = f"{row['Recession']} ({metric}: {row[metric]:.0f})"
            ax.plot(x_hist, hist_norm.values, color=colors[i],
                    linewidth=1.8, linestyle="--", alpha=0.85, label=label)

        ax.set_title(
            f"{indicator} — Normalised Trend (1 Year Before Recession/Today)",
            fontsize=11
        )
        ax.set_xlabel("Months Before Recession Start / Today (0 = recession start / today)")
        ax.set_ylabel("Normalised Value [0–1]")
        ax.legend(fontsize=9, loc="upper left")
        ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)
        ax.set_xlim(-n_months - 0.5, 0.5)

        plt.suptitle(
            f"Current Indicator Trends vs Top 2 Matches ({metric})\n"
            "(1-Year Look-back Window, Min-Max Normalised)",
            fontsize=13
        )
        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()</code></pre>
                </details>

